To Jed and Paul:<P>

I have several questions for you.
<P>
1)   If McNamara is truly guilty of war crimes, then surely his immediate subordinates 
are also guilty.  Then there's the Joint Chiefs. (I guess maybe they're his immediate 
subordinates - I don't know the nuances of the bureaucracy.)  Then there's the various 
civilian secretaries of each branch of the Armed Forces.  Then there's the subchiefs, 
such as the Chief of Naval Operations.  Then there's the theatre commanders (CINCPAC, 
etc.).  Then there's the Division CG's.  Well, you get the picture.  Just where do you 
draw the line?  Jed, I believe it was you who said the common soldier was not 
responsible for these crimes, but only those who ordered him to commit those crimes.  
Again I ask, on what basis can you make such a distinction?
<P>
2)  Let's presume McNamara really is a war criminal, and should be held responsible for 
war crimes.  What does that entail?  Should he be hanged if found guilty?  Imprisoned?  
What, exactly, do you suggest?
<P>
3)  What do you hope to accomplish?  Do you think the dialogue that is so desperately 
needed between people with opposing views of the war will be encouraged by labelling 
McNamara a war criminal?
<P>
4)  You wish to "tell the truth" about the war.  Fine, I'm all for that.  Maybe you can 
tell me what the truth is?  I saw it first hand, I've studied it in one way or another 
every day since I got back, and I STILL don't know what the "truth" is.  I'm not stupid, 
or a slow learner.  I just see too many shades of grey.  I will say it again, as I've 
said it before: I think the war was wrong and a tragic mistake.  That is one "truth" I 
suspect we'll agree on.
<P>
One last comment (or maybe two comments):  I am not a believer in war.  I know it first- 
hand, and it sucks.  When President Reagan came to Eureka in 1984, I organized a 
demonstration against his nuclear arms policy and his policies in Central America.  This 
was at some risk to my career, as the administration of the college felt tremendous 
pressure from some of the trustees and from the outside community to "get rid of the 
trouble-makers."  God forbid that Reagan encounter dissent on his home turf, and on his 
birthday, too.  But the administration also believes in something called academic freedom, and they knew some of my history.  I do not completely reject war, as I can imagine some 
circumstances in which it becomes "necessary".  
<P>
Comment number two:  war, whether "necessary" or not, is not fought according to international law.  There is no law in war.  Maybe that's a point we can agree on, too.
<P>
