You ask what would it entail to hold McNamara accountable for his actions.  First of all -- most important of all -- it entails that we must recognize the truth.  Ultimately, we must do this publicly. This is the only way I can see to restore our national honor, to make amends, to admit wrongdoing.  Only by admitting it, naming it do we have the possibility of avoiding it in the future.  What happens to McNamara at this point in time is entirely secondary to the need for us to publicly acknowledge that our leaders were guilty of war crimes.
<P>
As for hanging our former defense secretary,  I do not believe in the death penalty, so that's entirely out for me.  I believe in reparations, so I suggest he be sent to Vietnam to do some form of repair work.  
<P>
In terms of where to draw the lines of responsibility for what happened, this is a matter for a war crimes tribunal to decide.  Kissinger's crimes are the only others that should automatically be addressed, primarily because his crimes have been so thoroughly forgotten, and thus we have all become implicated in them after the fact.  We need to unambiguously repudiate not just what he did, but the entire process of normalization that has gone ever since then.  If Kissinger is a normal high official, then we are better off scraping our nation and starting over from scratch.
<P>
You say that wars are not fought according to international law.  But international law represents an ongoing attempt to curb, control and ultimately eliminate war.  The US has played a very important role in this process, when we have been led by our highest principles.  The Kellogg-Briand Pact of 1928 outlawed war entirely.  It was *OUR* idea. Kellogg was the American secretary of state.  Obviously it was not entirely successful but it's still in force.  And we have continued with other efforts to curb, control and eliminate war, including the establishment of the UN, and numerous treaties controlling or completely outlawing different kinds of weapons.  If at first you don't succede...
<P>
Some people say that war is inevitable and eternal, that we've always had it and we always will.  That was said about slavery in the middle of the last century.  It is simply not true.  There is nothing necessary about war.  Everything is in our power, but we must first be willing to confront OUR responsibility in these matters.
<P>
