Subject: A question of rhetoric and responsibility
<P>
Paul:
<P>
You have hit a button from the early 1970s when we were called "war criminals" even as we were getting off our freedom bird.  I saw the same shrillness now in what you have written as then, with the protesters at the airport and other places.  Perhaps you are reaping in my anger now the results of  the protests staged by you and others in the 1970s.  I know what it feels like to be on the receiving end of these kinds of charges.
<P>
Your anarchist orientation showed through in your postings. There is nothing you can do to tell me that any of our elected officials are war criminals.  First, they are innocent until proven guilty, beyond a reasonable doubt.  You have your beliefs, and I have mine.  We aren't going to convince each other on this one. I do know that this concept is engraved
into our constitution.
<P>
Concerning the issue of the difference between calling Calley a war criminal and McNamara, the latter has never been tried.  There is a legal, and a moral, difference.  I am not a lawyer (thank God), but I do believe there is a difference between the laws in black and white, and the context in which an alleged crime is committed. (Ever see "Les Miserables"?)
<P>
You have a responsibility to act with decency, and not to incite others to violence.  As I have said, I am very concerned about both the left and right wings in this country, and the degree of polarization I'm seeing.  Your words can take someone over the edge, just as can the words of some radio talk-show hosts.  People will be reading these posts, and we need to be responsible in the manner, as well as the content, with which we make our presentation.
<P>
I think one of the legacies of the Vietnam War is a protest movement that is deeply entrenched in its positions, and absolute in its convictions. Therein lies a danger; that of not being able to see the other side of the coin.  What was the old Indian saying, about not judging people until you have walked a mile in their moccasins?  I see in you and some of the others in the protest movement an inability to see anything outside your very narrow strictures. (I use this word in the context of an abnormal constricting of a canal.)  I see in this legacy the justification of many people on the extreme fringe of society for taking the initiative with terrorism.
<P>
